Baseline model

Ministries that We Want: Parties’ Agendas and Signaling of Portfolio Salience

Model

Let \(p\) denote the parties (i.e., \(p = 1, ..., P\)), \(t\) the year, and \(j\) the portfolios. For each party \(p\) in year \(t\) in portfolio \(j\) we have four corresponding values \(y_{k}\), with \(k\) indexing the \(K=4\) indicators we defined previously (amendments to the budget, indications, bills, and words in speeches). These values, moreover, were all recoded to ordinal categorical variables with 7 categories each (DESCRIBE LATER). In other words, \(y_{ptjk}\) orders the portfolios towards which parties directed legislative actions in a given year.

With our main variables, there are two latent quantities of interest we want to estimate: 1) the portfolio salience over time, i.e., a measure of how important a given cabinet portfolio is; and 2) the party preferences over portfolios, i.e., how much a given party prefer beyond its latent value. With both quantities, we could rank portfolio by a measure of salience that is free of party influence; and, at the same time, we could also investigate which parties value more some portfolio over others. The first quantity we wish to estimate, \(\theta_{jt}\), can vary across years and portfolios and we call latent portfolio salience. The second quantity, \(\lambda_{pj}\), that varies over parties and portfolios, is the latent party preferences, or party effects.

As is common in Item Reponse Theory (IRT) applications, we also define \(\beta_{k}\) discritionation parameters that captures how much a given indicator contributes to determine latent quantities; in addition, \(\alpha_{k}\) stand for \(K\) difficulty parameters. Both resemble the slope and the intercept in conventional regression model. Finally, we also define \(c\), that indicates the cutpoints to ordinal outputs (i.e., \(C = K - 1\)).

Having defined our main parameters, our link function is given by

\[ Pr[y_{ptjk = c}] = logit^{-1}([\theta_{jt} + \lambda_{pj}] \beta_{k} - \alpha_{kc}) - logit^{-1}([\theta_{jt} + \lambda_{pj}] \beta_{k-1} - \alpha_{kc-1}) \]

Instead of assuming indepence of indicators over time, we follow Author (AUTHOR) and Author (AUTHOR) and introduce a robust, dynamic component in our model. In particular, we assume that latent portfolio in any subsequent year depends on the value estimated on the previous. We do this by placing a non-informative prior to the first year of our series

\[ \theta_{pjt1} \sim N(0, 2) \] then, for all the other years we assume that \(\theta_{pj}\) is drawn from a Student’s T distribution with mean equal the previous value, i.e. \(\theta_{pjt-1}\), plus a random noise (or innovation)

\[ \theta_{pjt} \sim T_{4}(\theta_{pjt-1}, \sigma)~\forall t = 2,...,T \\ \sigma = 1 \] where \(T_{4}(\cdot)\) represents the Student’s T distribution with 4 degrees of freedom and \(\sigma\) is set to 1. As pointed by Authors (AUTHORS), Student’s T, with its long tail distribution, is better suited to model sudden or radical changes in latent quantities across years and units without compromising efficiency and avoiding bias. That is the reason that motivates our choice, although we note that we achive similar (?) results with non-informative normal-priors.

For the other priors, we employ the following (where \(HN\) is the half-normal distribution covering only positive values)

\[ \beta_{k} \sim HN(0, 3)\\ \alpha_{k} \sim N(0, 1)\\ \lambda_{pj} \sim N(0, 2) \]

To fit the model to the data, we run 4 Marcov Chain Monte Carlo chains with 8000 iterations each using Stan sampler and discarding the first X and using the latter X in the analysis that follows. Conventional diagnostics all indicate that chains have mixed well.
